{
  "style": "",
  "texts": [
    "By Theorem 6.3 the idempotent splitting of the ∞-category of 𝑑-excisive functors is given byExc 𝑑 * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q ≃ Mod Q (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S [𝑒 -1 𝑑]) × Mod Q (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S [(1 -𝑒 𝑑) -1]) ≃ Mod Q (𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S) × Mod Q (𝑃 𝑑-1 ℎ S) ≃ Mod Q (𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S) × Exc 𝑑-1 * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q,since 𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S inherits the structure of a commutative algebra object in Fun * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q through the equivalence 𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S ≃ 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S [𝑒 -1 𝑑].",
    "Through the equivalent descriptions of the splitting of Exc 𝑑 * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q the projection onto the second factor corresponds to the functor 𝑃 𝑑-1: Exc 𝑑 * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q -→ Exc 𝑑-1 * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q, and we may identify the fibre of this projection with the fibre of the functor 𝑃 𝑑-1, which is the ∞-category of 𝑑-homogeneous functors.",
    "It follows that the ∞-category of 𝑑-excisive functors splits asExc 𝑑 * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q ≃ Homog 𝑑 (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q × Exc 𝑑-1 * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q.",
    "The splitting as a product of ∞-categories of homogenous functors follows by reverse induction and the observation that there is an equivalence Homog 1 (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q ≃ Exc 1 * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q since all functors are assumed reduced.",
    "□The proof of Theorem 6.4 has the following immediate corollary, which amounts to the observation that rational homogeneous functor 𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S admits the structure of a commutative algebra object in Fun * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q.Corollary 6.5."
  ],
